flowRoot.flowPara: Ability of Pathway Methods to recover well-known Mutations

A. Volcano plot of associations of known driver mutations with our predicted pathway activity. Effect size on the horizontal axis, FDR-adjusted p-values on the vertical axis. Positive effect sizes (green circles) indicate that a gene mutated (HGNCmut) activates (→) a pathway, negative (red) that in inactivates (⊣). Empty circles are only significant if the tissue effect is not regressed out.

B. Performance of competing pathway methods in recovering known mutation-pathway associations derived from a linear model between mutated an not mutated samples within each tissue (p53, KRAS, STK11) or total (VHL). Pathways on the vertical axis, methods on the horizontal. Different p-value cutoffs due to number of mutations indicated in each plot. Our method is the only that is able to link TP53 mutations to p53 signaling, KRAS mutations to EGFR/MAPK, VHL to hypoxia and STK11 to apoptosis.

flowRoot.flowPara: Performance of signatures on basal gene expression

A. Comparison of commonly used methods to infer pathway activity from gene expression. Gene Ontology (GO) and simple pathway enrichment (top panel) using Reactome, KEGG, BioCarta, etc. treat the pathway members as gene sets, where the enrichment score is usually calculated using Gene Set Enrichment Analysis (GSEA). Other methods (middle panel) incorporate the structure of the pathway and known activating or inhibiting edges. SPIA uses curated edges from the KEGG database, Pathifier infers pathway structure from the data. PARADIGM explicitly models the transition from signaling molecule mRNA to protein to activity, yet the non-commercial version published in 2009 did not use any other data than gene expression and did not infer activity from gene expression downstream of the pathway. In contrast, our method of inferring pathway-responsive genes looks at the footprint of known signaling activity instead of the pathway members themselves.

B. Inferred pathway scores of our method for different TCGA cohorts where matched tissue normals are available, expressed as standard deviations over the median of normal samples. It captures e.g. the importance of VEGF and PI3K in Breast Cancer (BRCA) or the high activity of MAPK in Colon- and Rectal Cancer (COAD/READ), while other methods do not (cf. supplementary figure).

C. Associations of pathway scores with known driver mutations (left panel). Effect size on the horizontal axis, FDR-adjusted p-values on the vertical. Positive matches between driver mutations that are known to activate or deactivate a pathway are: (1) TP53 mutations deactivate p53 signaling, (2) VHL mutations activate the hypoxic response, (3) KRAS and NRAS mutations activate MAPK and/or EGFR-responsive genes, and STK11 mutations abrogate apoptosis (Trail pathway). Less well known, our approach also identifies TP53 Gain of Function mutations and links them to PI3K-responsive genes. This is in stark contrast to other pathway methods (right panel), where only Gene Ontology (GO) identifies a much weaker deactivation of p53 and the rest do not. For KRAS (lower panel), our method is also the only one that reports a significant interaction with the MAPK pathway in the right direction. This is similar for other mutations where any pathway methods produces hits, as shown in supplementary figure X.
D. Correlation of pathway-responsive genes for normals (top panel) and tumors (middle panel), as well as the significance of their difference (lower panel).
